<h2 style="text-align:center;">Replace with a Nice Title</h2><p style="text-align:center;">Kentaro Takiguchi, Yifan Tang, Yuchi Liu, Zijie Liang, Si Chen, Chang Zhao</p><h4>ABSTRACT</h4><p>A brief description of the key points in the report.</p><h3>1 &nbsp;INTRODUCTION</h3><p>The background of the problem.</p><h3>2 &nbsp;Data Preparation</h3><p>What data manipulation was necessary to create a dataset for analysis.</p><h3>3 &nbsp;Data Exploration</h3><p>What you learned from your initial analysis of the data.</p><h3>4 &nbsp;Modeling</h3><p>In order to figure out which data has influence on the productivity of the country the most, we trained two different types of models and examined how each data contributed to prediction based on the assumption that its feature importance represents the influence on productivity. For reproducibility, we published the implementation on GitHub with documentation and tests.</p><h4>4.1 &nbsp;Experiment Settings</h4><p>Since the compensation data is provided as a time-series dataset, we split data by period. The records from 2010 to 2015 were used for training and the records from 2016 to 2018 were used for validation. RMSE (Root Mean Square Error) was used as a metric denoted as follows:</p><p style="text-align:center;"><math style="font-family:stix;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>R</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac><munderover><mo>âˆ‘</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></munderover><msup><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>y</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mover><mi>y</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></math></p><p>where&nbsp;<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mi>y</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></math><i>&nbsp;</i>is&nbsp;the&nbsp;value to&nbsp;predict&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mover><mi>y</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi>i</mi></msub></math><i>&nbsp;</i>is&nbsp;the&nbsp;predicted&nbsp;value. This metric shows how accurate the model&nbsp;predicts.</p><h4>4.2 &nbsp;Feature Engineering</h4><p>We hypothesized that productivity of the year is affected by data from past years. For example, the education data shows the percentage of people who are in education or training, meaning that they are basically not earning money at this moment. Therefore, predicting the current year's productivity using the current year's features may not be appropriate. For that reason, we created lagged features to capture trends and used it for training. However, it was challenging to capture long-term trends since the available year range is limited. If we create a feature using features in the last 5 years, only a few records remain for training, which makes training a model infeasible.</p><p>In order to determine the reasonable time range for lagged features, we computed the correlation matrix as shown in Figure 1 where the suffix "shift_n" indicates that data is from n year(s) ago. It can be seen that shift_1 features and shift_2 features are highly correlated. In addition, we checked performance on a simple model trained using shift_n features. shift_2 features showed slightly better performance than models trained using shift_1 features but the model used shift_2 features was trained with lesser data and hence, the performance may be less reliable. Though training model using older data may or may not give us higher accuracy, we chose to train models using shift_1 features to make our analysis more robust.</p><p>Since the objective of this work is to locate what factor determines the productivity of the country, not achieving high accuracy, we intendedly did not use features that may improve accuracy of the model such as past productivity of the country and statistics on features such as min, max, mean, and diff to focus on examining individual features.</p><p>Features are scaled in the range of 0 to 1 since the ranges of features vary, which makes some machine learning algorithms not working properly.</p><figure class="image"><img src="data:image/png;base64,"><figcaption>Figure 1: Part of correlation matrix of features</figcaption></figure><h4>4.3 &nbsp;Simple Explainable Model</h4><p>First, we trained a linear regression model that is formulated as follows:</p><p style="text-align:center;"><math style="font-family:stix;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>Î²</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><munderover><mo>âˆ‘</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></munderover><msub><mi>Î²</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></math></p><p>where xi is a feature and Î²i is a weight on the feature. The advantage of this method is its simplicity, enabling us to examine how feature contributed to predicting productivity by checking coefficients. importance of GBDT</p><p>Table 3 compares performance of different models trained using the same features. The tuned LightGBM considerably outperformed a LightGBM model with the default configuration and a linear regression model. We visualized predicted compensation along with the actual values. As can be seen in Figure 2, the tuned LightGBM outputs reasonable predictions for analysis.</p><figure class="table"><table><tbody><tr><td><figure class="image"><img src="data:image/png;base64,"><figcaption>(a) Predictions on Bulgari</figcaption></figure></td><td><figure class="image"><img src="data:image/png;base64,"><figcaption>(b) Predictions on Norway</figcaption></figure></td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p style="text-align:center;">Figure 2: How accurate each model is</p><p>LightGBM also provides a function measuring feature importance. There are several methods to measure fea ture importance in tree models, LightGBM provides two options: split-based and gain-based methods. The splitbased measure counts how many times the feature is used to split the tree, and the gain-based measure computes the total gains of splits. Table 3 shows feature importance computed by the split-based algorithm which is the default algorithm of LightGBM.</p><p>The result is quite different from the one of the linear regression model. While the GBDT places importance on population, the coefficient is low in the linear regression models. It motivated us to investigate another method to examine feature importance to conclude our findings.</p><h4>4.5 &nbsp;Explanation of Predictions</h4><p>Simple models are often preferred for their ease of interpretation even if they may be less accurate than complex ones. However, using complex models is more beneficial when the number of features grows as shown in Figure <a href="#_bookmark4"><span style="color:windowtext;">2.</span></a> The problem of using GBDT is that it is unclear if splitting counts represents significance on the target value. In order to overcome this trade-off issue, we applied SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlpanations) <a href="#_bookmark11"><span style="color:windowtext;">[3]&nbsp;</span></a>to GBDT.</p><p>SHAP is a tool for explainable machine learning. SHAP uses classic equations from cooperative game theory to compute explanations of model predictions: Shapley regression values. Shapley regression values are feature importances for linear models in the presence of multicollinearity. This method requires retraining the model on all feature subsets S F , where F is the set of all features. The effect of a feature set is computed by taking a weighted average of all possible combinations with and without the feature set as follows:</p><p style="text-align:center;"><math style="font-family:stix;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mi>Ï•</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><munder><mo>âˆ‘</mo><mrow><mi>S</mi><mo>âŠ†</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>\</mo><mo>{</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>}</mo></mrow></munder><mfrac><mrow><mfenced close="|" open="|"><mi>S</mi></mfenced><mo>!</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfenced close="|" open="|"><mi>F</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced close="|" open="|"><mi>S</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>!</mo></mrow><mrow><mfenced close="|" open="|"><mi>F</mi></mfenced><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac><mfenced close="]" open="["><mrow><msub><mi>f</mi><mrow><mi>S</mi><mo>âˆª</mo><mo>{</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>}</mo></mrow></msub><mfenced><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>U</mi><mo>{</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>}</mo></mrow></msub></mfenced><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>S</mi></msub><mfenced><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>S</mi></msub></mfenced></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>Figure 4 is the summary plot showing the positive and negative relationships of the predictors with the target value rendered by SHAP. Each dot represents a data instance. Features are ranked in descending order. The horizontal location shows whether the effect of that value is associated with a higher or lower prediction. Color shows whether that variable is high or low for that observation. We can see that HRST and R&amp;D expenditure show a clear tendency: the higher feature values are, the higher productivity is.</p><figure class="image"><img src="data:image/png;base64,"><figcaption>Figure 4: Summary plot of SHAP values</figcaption></figure><p>Table&nbsp;<a href="#_bookmark8"><span style="color:windowtext;">4&nbsp;</span></a>compares features importances measured by different methods. Note that their scales are different because of the difference of the nature of their algorithms.
